<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-632-935  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 632 935.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Nov 26 1990 v7 n47 p71(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Lotus and Banyan could be a perfect match. (Lotus DevelopmentCorp., Banyan Systems Inc.) (editorial)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Whitmore, Sam.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Lotus Development Corp. (Acquisitions and mergers)Banyan Systems Inc. (Acquisitions and mergers).andO;Ticker:    LOTS.andO;Topic:     MergerSoftware PublishersMarket AnalysisAcquisitionNetwork SoftwareNetwork Operating Systems.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Forget about Lotus's possible acquisition of Samna.andP;  A more strategic marketexists for Lotus: network-based applications and network-systems software.andM;Lotus eyed this target when it tried to acquire Novell earlier this year.andO;Lotus shouldn't give up.andP;  It should buy Banyan before someone else does.andM;Lotus and Banyan need each other.andP;  Their customers will soon demandapplications that are tightly integrated with networks; it's too late foreither Lotus or Banyan to do that alone.andM;Microsoft and Novell are already well on their way.andP;  Microsoft is working toblend SQL Server and various third-party front ends with its own LAN Manager,and intends to sell these products to corporations as integrated departmentalsolutions.andM;Novell, with its NetWare Comunications Services Manager package and itsBTrieve SQL server, has the same aspirations.andM;Neither Lotus nor Banyan can enter this fray alone.andP;  True, Lotus has aversion of 1-2-3 for every important hardware platform; true, Banyan'sUnix-based, scalable VINES architecture links well to minis and mainframes.andO;However, corporate systems architects seek vendors who can and will takeresponsibility for both kinds of software.andM;Banyan faces a potential death threat from Novell and Microsoft, both of whomwill be spending billions of dollars to capture the networking aficionadosthat traditionally have been Banyan's best customers.andM;Even the geography works in the two firms' favor.andP;  With Banyan located inWestboro, Mass., and Lotus only 30 miles away in Cambridge, Mass., the twofirms could blend with a fraction of the effort that plagued the ill-fatedLotus-Novell merger.andM;Lotus would stand a better chance of succeeding with its Unix strategy if itwere to bind with a Unix-based network operating system like VINES.andP;  Acombination of Unix networking and application software, scalable across PCs,minis and mainframes, would benefit both firms.andM;Today, Lotus pays its bills by selling stand-alone applications.andP;  Banyansurvives by selling networks.andP;  Maybe they should have lunch togethersometime, before they become lunch for someone else.andM;----------By Sam Whitmore</TEXT></DOC>